<div id="review_2719520636" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2719520636" />
    <a title="Cindy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2058617-cindy"><img alt="Cindy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576473595p2/2058617.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2719520636?book_show_action=true">Feb 17, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cindy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cindy" href="/user/show/2058617-cindy">Cindy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2058617-cindy?shelf=absolute-favorites">absolute-favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2058617-cindy?shelf=newbery-titles">newbery-titles</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2719520636" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer964687977695683028">I just reread this wonderful story this past week, and cannot believe that I had forgotten to include it in my Goodreads list! Not only that, but it should have been in my “absolute favorites” shelf (but it is now!)! <br/>I not only loved this story, but I learned a lot as well! This tale is about a young orphan named Tree-ear, who lives in 12th century Korea. He hides out in the bushes and watches one of the local potters working at his wheel, and longs to learn his craft. Until I read this story, I</span>
  <span id="freeText964687977695683028" style="display:none">I just reread this wonderful story this past week, and cannot believe that I had forgotten to include it in my Goodreads list! Not only that, but it should have been in my “absolute favorites” shelf (but it is now!)! <br />I not only loved this story, but I learned a lot as well! This tale is about a young orphan named Tree-ear, who lives in 12th century Korea. He hides out in the bushes and watches one of the local potters working at his wheel, and longs to learn his craft. Until I read this story, I had no idea about the history of Korean pottery! Turns out that the clay near the western coast of what is now South Korea was ideal for pottery. I looked up more information about it after finishing the book, and was so impressed! It is beautiful! <br />...But, back to the story. Min, the elderly potter whom Tree-ear spies on, is a meticulous artist, and the boy is in awe of his work. One day, Tree-ear sneaks up to the shelves to inspect the fine details of Min’s work, and accidentally breaks some pieces. The old potter catches him and responds in anger. The boy asks if he can work off the cost of the damaged items. Thus Tree-ear begins his journey into learning the art of building and firing clay to make beautiful and useful items. Then, his life and the life of his master may change forever, because an emissary from the emperor’s court comes to their small village to look at all the local pottery. If their work is chosen, the potter selected would be granted a royal commission, which is a great honor and would guarantee a lifetime of work. <br />***If you love historical fiction, or have an interest in pottery, then treat yourself to this sweet, charming 2002 Newbery winner. It is a treasure.</span>
  <a data-text-id="964687977695683028" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


